No, the early ones stopped
just when his life got interesting.

24:30.168 --> 24:32.466
Sounds quite interesting already.

24:32.571 --> 24:36.007
- Where's John?
- He's gone to Leicester to see the sister.

24:36.208 --> 24:39.177
<i>To look at the house</i>
<i>where Joe was brought up.</i>

24:48.720 --> 24:49.846
Hello.

24:50.255 --> 24:52.314
Was this the Orton house?

24:55.160 --> 24:57.253
Is this the...

24:58.163 --> 25:01.326
- I'm English. Ask me.
- Was this the house that Orton...

25:01.399 --> 25:02.889
<i>I hated that house.</i>

25:03.034 --> 25:05.264
There was no love in it.

25:05.437 --> 25:08.065
No wonder he couldn't wait to get out.

25:08.173 --> 25:11.438
In those days, if you were from Leicester
and wanted to be an actor...

25:11.510 --> 25:13.501
you had to get rid of your accent.

25:13.578 --> 25:15.512
Not that Mom knew anything
about the acting.

25:15.580 --> 25:18.879
<i>- She just wanted John to talk posh.</i>
<i>- You still call him John.</i>

25:18.950 --> 25:23.546
<i>That was his name when we were little.</i>
<i>It was after he was famous, he was Joe.</i>

25:23.755 --> 25:26.315
- Mrs. Lambert?
- Madame Lambert.

25:29.160 --> 25:33.028
- You are anxious to improve your diction?
- Yes, Madame Lambert.

25:33.431 --> 25:35.422
What is your chosen field?

25:36.268 --> 25:38.793
- I want to be an actor.
- Indeed.

25:39.204 --> 25:41.764
Leicester has produced some fine actors.

25:41.873 --> 25:44.967
Leicester is the hometown
of Richard Attenborough.

25:45.143 --> 25:46.132
Tea.

25:46.311 --> 25:49.439
Movement, elocution,
all these I can teach you.

25:49.514 --> 25:51.414
The arts proper to the stage.

25:51.483 --> 25:53.883
How to smoke a cigarette
with poise, elegance...

25:53.952 --> 25:56.011
and, above all, conviction.

25:56.087 --> 25:58.817
The powder compact
as a means of expression.

25:58.890 --> 26:00.585
Go to any production in the West End...

26:00.659 --> 26:04.117
and you will see these arts
brought to a pitch of perfection.

26:04.195 --> 26:07.596
But all that is as nothing...

26:08.466 --> 26:11.094
without the one essential requirement.

26:11.269 --> 26:13.897
- I have the money.
- Money? Pish!

26:14.406 --> 26:17.864
I'm not speaking of money.
I'm speaking of talent.

26:18.577 --> 26:21.808
Judging by what you've read,
you have no talent.

26:22.347 --> 26:24.212
No talent whatsoever.

26:24.449 --> 26:27.316
- I still want to learn.
- Bravo!

26:27.786 --> 26:32.052
No marks for talent.
Full marks for Dunkirk spirit.

26:40.465 --> 26:41.796
Bloody plays.

26:41.866 --> 26:44.334
Mom didn't have much of a horizon.

26:44.603 --> 26:48.699
She'd have liked him a civil servant.
A suit every day of his life.

26:48.940 --> 26:52.103
Next time, tell them
to provide you with a costume!

26:53.345 --> 26:56.280
Using our bedspread. Wicked!

26:56.715 --> 26:57.841
You'll clean it!

27:00.352 --> 27:02.377
Coloring it with distemper.

27:02.454 --> 27:04.547
Ruined, bloody ruined.

27:05.023 --> 27:08.550
I bet Dirk Bogarde
didn't distemper his mother's bedspread!

27:09.661 --> 27:10.958
Bloody disgusting.

27:18.036 --> 27:20.004
And get some clothes on.

27:21.039 --> 27:24.531
Walking around like Sambo.
Don't know where to look.

27:39.057 --> 27:40.149
What?

27:40.558 --> 27:42.856
There's somebody at the door.
Fetch us me teeth.

27:54.739 --> 27:57.139
It'll be the gas man. I never paid.

28:00.278 --> 28:01.768
Good afternoon.

28:02.113 --> 28:04.775
I'm a Council official.
I've come about your lad.

28:04.849 --> 28:07.477
Why? What's he done?
What have you done?

28:07.552 --> 28:10.817
Shakespeare's what he's done.
He's taken a very good part.

28:10.889 --> 28:14.256
He's favorably impressed a prominent
member of the Education Committee.

28:14.325 --> 28:16.156
Yes, he'd have a bedspread.

28:18.563 --> 28:19.962
Good afternoon.

28:20.031 --> 28:22.329
- Who's this?
- This is my husband. Ignore him.

28:22.400 --> 28:25.631
- Your son is a born actor.
- An actor?

28:25.704 --> 28:28.036
But he went to Clark's College.
He's done shorthand.

28:28.106 --> 28:31.269
- He had a badge in his blazer.
- This boy will never make a typist.

28:31.342 --> 28:33.310
- He can do 40 words a minute.
- Shut up!

28:33.378 --> 28:35.471
No, he must take up a dramatic career.

28:35.547 --> 28:39.506
But I've sacrificed all down the line
in order for him to land a job in an office.

28:39.584 --> 28:43.748
No, Mrs. Orton, your son must go in
for a scholarship to RADA.

28:44.155 --> 28:47.613
- RADA?
- The Royal Academy of Dramatic Art.

28:48.059 --> 28:49.151
RADA?

28:51.429 --> 28:53.829
The Royal Academy of Dramatic Art.

28:54.666 --> 28:55.792
RADA.

28:58.103 --> 29:00.663
"Do you know who I'm looking for, Smee?"

29:00.739 --> 29:03.299
"No, tell me again, Captain."

29:03.575 --> 29:06.635
"I'm looking for a boy, Smee."

29:08.079 --> 29:10.138
"What kind of boy, Captain?"

29:10.582 --> 29:13.551
"A wicked boy. A heartless boy.

29:13.651 --> 29:16.711
"A boy who never ate his rice pudding."

29:17.055 --> 29:20.320
"Oh, horror! Can there be such boys?"

29:20.558 --> 29:22.219
"Aye, there can.

29:22.494 --> 29:26.555
"It was a boy like that that cut off my arm...

29:26.765 --> 29:28.960
"and fed it to the crocodiles.

29:29.100 --> 29:30.397
"His name...

29:30.468 --> 29:33.437
"was Peter Pan."

29:45.450 --> 29:48.578
You've had some amateur experience,
I gather, Mr. Orton.

29:48.720 --> 29:50.347
Tell us about it.

29:51.256 --> 29:53.690
I started off in <i>Richard III.</i>

29:54.159 --> 29:55.421
As what?

29:56.227 --> 29:57.592
A messenger.

29:59.964 --> 30:03.331
That was most original.
You've done very well.

30:04.402 --> 30:06.632
Yes, very nice and loud.

30:17.615 --> 30:21.813
"O, that this too too solid flesh
would melt...

30:21.986 --> 30:25.319
- "thaw and resolve itself into a dew!"
- Rather old.

30:25.423 --> 30:28.620
- "Or that the Everlasting had not fix'd..."
- Not as old as he looks.

30:28.693 --> 30:31.093
"...his canon 'gainst self-slaughter!"

30:32.730 --> 30:35.255
It's useful to have somebody as old as that.

30:35.733 --> 30:37.394
Just for casting.

30:38.169 --> 30:41.730
We seem to be taking
practically anything that stands up.

30:45.243 --> 30:46.733
At least he's got the coat.

30:55.220 --> 30:57.688
- What are you?
- Cats, miss.

30:58.957 --> 31:01.619
Let's change the exercise slightly.

31:02.327 --> 31:04.090
I've got a cat now.

31:05.797 --> 31:08.288
Here you are. Catch it.

31:58.983 --> 32:02.885
Movement, enunciation, breath control.

32:03.288 --> 32:06.052
It's all so wildly dated, don't you agree?

32:07.091 --> 32:10.891
- Yes, it is.
- Still, I suppose the beginners find it useful.

32:11.562 --> 32:13.757
- Are you new to London?
- Hardly.

32:14.966 --> 32:18.458
A small legacy enabled me to spend
several weekends at the Strand Palace.

32:18.536 --> 32:22.199
- Hotels are a closed book to me.
- You'll like the Strand Palace.

32:22.273 --> 32:24.707
Perhaps we might venture there one evening
for coffee.

32:24.776 --> 32:25.902
Ready?

32:25.977 --> 32:28.878
We're off over to South Bank. The festival.

32:29.514 --> 32:31.414
Yes, it might be amusing, I suppose.

32:31.482 --> 32:34.610
Yes, the plebs and their simple pleasures.

32:36.087 --> 32:38.112
What did you ask him for?

32:49.133 --> 32:50.361
Come on.

33:02.513 --> 33:03.946
"Let us go then, you and I...

33:04.015 --> 33:06.415
"when the evening is spread out
against the sky...

33:06.484 --> 33:09.180
"like a patient etherised upon a table."

33:12.390 --> 33:13.652
Come on.

33:18.863 --> 33:21.093
You know, some of these people are...

33:22.467 --> 33:25.231
- having sexual intercourse.
- Fucking, you mean.

33:25.303 --> 33:28.966
What did you expect?
Many of them are from Australia.

33:31.142 --> 33:32.336
Come on.

33:44.922 --> 33:47.186
<i>What was the Festival of Britain?</i>

33:47.759 --> 33:49.954
<i>That was when it all came off the ration.</i>

33:50.194 --> 33:52.185
<i>You mean food and things?</i>

33:52.330 --> 33:55.231
<i>Life, dear. Sex. Everything.</i>

33:56.434 --> 33:58.163
<i>Only it didn't, of course.</i>

34:04.575 --> 34:08.341
I wish he'd never come.
I wanted it to be just us.

34:14.118 --> 34:15.710
- No.
- Why?

34:15.820 --> 34:19.585
- Not here. People are looking.
- Fuck people.

34:19.924 --> 34:21.949
You can't live like that, John.

34:22.025 --> 34:24.893
- I want to take things gradually.
- I don't.

34:25.496 --> 34:27.521
You don't know what life's like.

34:27.697 --> 34:30.757
I'm not going to find out at this rate, either.

35:36.234 --> 35:38.725
- Thank you.
- Cheap clothes suit you.

35:38.803 --> 35:41.363
It's because you're from the gutter.

35:45.776 --> 35:48.006
I said I'll move in with Janet.

35:52.083 --> 35:53.744
This is the room.

35:54.685 --> 35:57.848
I'm only looking. I'm fixed up elsewhere.

36:04.162 --> 36:06.460
Is it a northern light?

36:07.165 --> 36:09.030
Never heard any complaints.

36:09.100 --> 36:12.035
Of course, it's in dire need of decorating.

36:13.104 --> 36:14.594
What is that smell?

36:15.072 --> 36:19.008
Air freshener.
The carpet came from Reading originally.

36:22.046 --> 36:23.707
Friends, are you?

36:24.015 --> 36:26.882
- Students.
- I've nothing against friendship.

36:27.385 --> 36:31.151
It's the most wonderful thing in the world,
within reason.

36:31.422 --> 36:33.049
I'm only looking.

36:33.524 --> 36:36.391
- They say Islington's coming up.
- It is.

36:36.661 --> 36:40.927
They've turned the greengrocer's into
an antique shop, and the pub is silent.

36:40.998 --> 36:42.590
What do you think?

36:43.134 --> 36:46.069
I think I shall keep an open mind.

37:05.756 --> 37:07.883
Help yourself. Here.

37:17.969 --> 37:21.928
- Where did you get them?
- I nicked them while he wasn't looking.

37:30.314 --> 37:32.839
- You can type?
- Forty words a minute.

37:33.551 --> 37:37.248
- Neither of us seems to have family photos.
- I'm an orphan.

37:37.455 --> 37:39.685
I always wanted to be an orphan.

37:39.757 --> 37:42.282
I could have been
if it hadn't been for my parents.

37:42.360 --> 37:44.624
My mother died when I was a boy.

37:45.396 --> 37:48.024
She was stung on the tongue by a wasp.

37:48.766 --> 37:51.667
One minute
we were just sitting down to breakfast...

37:51.736 --> 37:53.670
ten minutes later, she was dead.

37:53.738 --> 37:55.933
- That still leaves your dad.
- Him?

37:56.374 --> 37:59.002
He put his head in the gas oven
when I was 18.

37:59.076 --> 38:01.567
I came down one morning
and found him lying there.

38:01.646 --> 38:03.443
So I switched the gas off, had a shave...

38:03.514 --> 38:06.005
made some tea, and called the ambulance.
In that order.

38:06.083 --> 38:09.018
I understand.
My dad always took a back seat.

38:09.620 --> 38:10.951
My novels.

38:11.689 --> 38:13.281
Anybody can act.

38:14.358 --> 38:16.417
All these books. I'll never catch up.

38:16.494 --> 38:19.486
I'm a cultivated person, John.
You'll find it rubs off.

38:19.563 --> 38:20.962
Dictionaries.

38:21.032 --> 38:23.728
- Can you spell?
- Yes, but not accurately.

38:28.372 --> 38:33.002
- I don't understand Shakespeare.
- We'll cross that bridge when we come to it.

38:33.377 --> 38:36.471
Talking of Shakespeare,
we're missing the Queen.

38:56.434 --> 38:59.494
<i>I here present unto you Queen Elizabeth...</i>

39:00.171 --> 39:01.604
<i>your undoubted Queen.</i>

39:01.672 --> 39:02.661
Improves the contrast.

39:02.740 --> 39:06.301
<i>Wherefore all you who are come this day...</i>

39:06.844 --> 39:08.869
<i>to do your homage and service...</i>

39:09.280 --> 39:11.339
<i>are you willing to do the same?</i>

39:16.520 --> 39:18.886
This is a new experience for me.

39:20.224 --> 39:21.350
Yes?

39:21.992 --> 39:23.357
Television.

39:24.362 --> 39:26.387
I've never seen it before.

39:27.431 --> 39:30.594
<i>... to govern the peoples</i>
<i>of the United Kingdom...</i>

39:30.668 --> 39:32.101
Do you like it?

39:34.372 --> 39:35.464
This?

39:38.876 --> 39:40.241
Television.

39:42.813 --> 39:47.614
<i>... the other territories according to</i>
<i>their respective laws and customs?</i>

39:48.219 --> 39:50.380
<i>I solemnly promise so to do.</i>

40:11.041 --> 40:13.305
It's the beginning of a new era.

41:06.297 --> 41:10.199
<i>Thence goes Queen Elizabeth</i>
<i>to sit in King Edward's Chair...</i>

41:10.568 --> 41:13.731
<i>for the most sacred rite of her anointing.</i>

41:24.615 --> 41:26.776
Are you up here helping John?

41:26.851 --> 41:28.375
Holding his hand.

41:28.986 --> 41:31.614
Did Kenneth ever come up to Leicester?

41:33.591 --> 41:35.149
Did you like him?

41:36.327 --> 41:38.295
I didn't dislike him.

41:38.362 --> 41:40.887
I could see what he saw in Joe, after all.

41:41.532 --> 41:44.399
I couldn't really see what Joe saw in him.

41:44.869 --> 41:47.303
Of course, I didn't know what went on.

41:47.404 --> 41:49.531
Upstairs, come on.

41:51.375 --> 41:54.902
Did you know that Joe was that way?

41:57.014 --> 41:58.982
- Yes.
- You didn't.

41:59.049 --> 42:01.813
I did and I didn't.

42:02.720 --> 42:04.620
The way you do, don't you?

42:04.955 --> 42:09.358
Mind you, at our Douglas' wedding,
Mom found him in bed with a bridesmaid.

42:11.428 --> 42:14.158
So you see? It's as I say.

42:14.632 --> 42:17.032
He couldn't have learned it in Leicester.

42:17.101 --> 42:18.693
He was corrupted.

42:19.904 --> 42:22.065
Joe wanted something from Kenneth.

42:22.139 --> 42:25.074
And Kenneth wanted something from Joe.
It's not corruption.

42:25.609 --> 42:27.076
It's collaboration.

42:27.611 --> 42:30.739
He was born that way,
or else it was my mom.

42:30.814 --> 42:32.338
Women don't care anyway.

42:32.416 --> 42:35.817
- I don't care what men get up to.
- I don't care where they put it.

42:35.886 --> 42:38.150
As long as they don't put it there.

42:38.222 --> 42:40.190
Didn't I say upstairs?

42:40.691 --> 42:42.955
A taste of their own medicine.

42:45.362 --> 42:49.355
The lavatories shocked me a bit
when I read his diary, but...

42:50.601 --> 42:52.660
A boy stopped me the other day...

42:52.736 --> 42:56.365
and said, "I want to thank you for
your brother's plays." So what do you do?

42:56.440 --> 42:59.136
Yes, I feel quite grateful
for his plays myself.

42:59.677 --> 43:02.669
Personally, I think a lot of that is made up.

43:03.581 --> 43:05.640
- What?
- The toilets.

43:06.884 --> 43:09.546
You have to go into all that, do you?

43:12.790 --> 43:15.122
It all seems a bit unnecessary to me.

43:15.225 --> 43:18.820
The lawn mower is not unnecessary.
The Fiesta is not unnecessary.

43:18.896 --> 43:21.330
You ought to be grateful
we get money from his plays.

43:21.398 --> 43:24.128
Grateful? I work, too, you know.

43:24.835 --> 43:27.804
This isn't royalties.
This is plumbing money, this is.

43:27.871 --> 43:30.362
He's nothing in Leicester, Joe Orton.

43:31.809 --> 43:33.276
- Ken?
- What?

43:34.812 --> 43:37.713
You know you could be
put in prison for this.

43:37.781 --> 43:39.248
So could you.

43:40.217 --> 43:41.445
No.

43:42.953 --> 43:44.716
I'm the innocent party.

43:52.730 --> 43:54.698
No, I want to get on.

43:56.000 --> 43:58.833
Writing, John, is one-tenth inspiration,
nine-tenths...

43:58.902 --> 44:00.529
Masturbation.

44:39.810 --> 44:42.506
That's a library book.
You should respect books.

44:42.579 --> 44:46.015
I respect them more than you.
You just take them for granted.

44:50.521 --> 44:52.887
Shit, I'll never catch up.

44:53.257 --> 44:56.522
So what's this?
We are halfway through a novel.

44:57.828 --> 44:59.227
You are, you mean.

45:00.431 --> 45:02.626
It's a collaboration, dear.

45:04.568 --> 45:05.865
We've written it together.

45:05.936 --> 45:07.767
- Stop it, I'm reading.
- You're not.

45:07.838 --> 45:09.738
- Test me, then.
- What on?

45:09.807 --> 45:11.138
Mythology.

45:12.509 --> 45:14.238
Who is the father of Oedipus?

45:14.311 --> 45:16.245
- Laius.
- Who is his mother?

45:16.747 --> 45:18.214
Fuck his mother.

45:22.619 --> 45:24.086
<i>Boy Hairdresser.</i>

45:25.055 --> 45:26.352
Nice title.

45:26.990 --> 45:28.981
I've shown it to one or two...

45:29.660 --> 45:31.855
selected colleagues...

45:33.030 --> 45:35.498
- and we laughed.
- You're kidding.

45:36.233 --> 45:38.030
We had a real chuckle.

45:39.503 --> 45:42.438
The trouble is that normal sex...

45:43.073 --> 45:45.200
is still a novelty for most people...

45:45.576 --> 45:47.100
in book form.

45:48.112 --> 45:49.875
A book such as yours...

45:50.314 --> 45:53.750
- which very wittily...
- We thought it was witty.

45:55.486 --> 45:59.650
...explores the byways of sexuality...

46:00.858 --> 46:02.826
is ahead of its time.

46:04.962 --> 46:07.328
We are a very conservative firm.

46:13.971 --> 46:16.030
Isn't one of the directors T.S. Eliot?

46:16.907 --> 46:18.397
Yes, that's right.

46:18.475 --> 46:20.272
Is he in the building?

46:25.182 --> 46:27.150
Thursday. Yes, he is.

46:27.217 --> 46:30.482
Fancy, John,
we're under the same roof as T.S. Eliot.

46:34.491 --> 46:36.823
He wants to know which is his chair.

46:40.130 --> 46:41.358
This one.

46:47.538 --> 46:50.302
Yes, well, thank you very much
for letting us see this.

46:50.374 --> 46:54.777
You can keep it a little longer if you want.
Show it to a few more friends.

46:55.145 --> 46:56.635
Thank you, no.

46:59.516 --> 47:02.451
And remember, next time you see Mr. Eliot...

47:03.086 --> 47:05.919
tell him he has two devoted fans
in Islington...

47:05.989 --> 47:08.890
who think <i>The Waste Land</i>
is a real knockout.

47:12.796 --> 47:13.820
Never mind.

47:13.897 --> 47:16.889
At least you can say
you sat in the same chair as T.S. Eliot.

47:16.967 --> 47:19.492
Yes, I'm never gonna wipe my bum again.

47:20.304 --> 47:23.762
Why did you leave all the talking to me?
It's your book as much as mine.

47:23.841 --> 47:26.036
I'm shy. It's not my territory.

47:27.978 --> 47:29.741
This is dead-center me.

47:32.549 --> 47:33.846
Nice bum.

47:33.917 --> 47:35.942
- He heard that.
- So what?

47:36.587 --> 47:38.054
Now you're shy.

47:41.258 --> 47:44.159
This is Mr. Halliwell.

47:46.563 --> 47:47.962
Really?

47:48.832 --> 47:50.925
Doesn't knock on my box one bit.

47:52.502 --> 47:54.231
He's got a big one.

47:56.974 --> 48:00.137
- How do you know?
- It's written all over his face.

48:03.647 --> 48:06.810
- Look at the package on that.
- Where?

48:08.418 --> 48:10.716
- We're on.
- I didn't see anything. What did he do?

48:10.787 --> 48:12.516
What do you want, a telegram? Come on!

48:24.034 --> 48:26.468
He's built like a brick shithouse.

48:27.804 --> 48:31.262
- He's probably a policeman.
- Yes, I know. Isn't he wonderful?

48:50.394 --> 48:52.760
We've got tickets for the Proms.

49:14.217 --> 49:16.617
All right. What's your name?

49:17.120 --> 49:19.611
- What do you mean, what's my name?
- Mine's Kevin.

49:19.690 --> 49:21.180
Mine's Howard.

49:21.725 --> 49:24.159
- That's a poncey name.
- Patrick, then.

49:24.361 --> 49:27.228
Catholic, are you? What do you do?

49:27.531 --> 49:30.329
- I don't know. What do you do?
- I'm a fitter, car components.

49:30.400 --> 49:31.492
I'm a dog handler.

49:31.568 --> 49:34.696
On an individual basis,
or are you a tool of a large organization?

49:34.771 --> 49:38.707
I'm so shit scared, I don't know
